description:
sync.ts:52 runs git push without specifying a remote or upstream:

  execFileSync('git', ['push'], { cwd: worktreePath });

Newly-created agent worktrees (from camper init) have no tracking branch configured. This fails with 'fatal: The current branch has no upstream branch' the first time camper sync is run on a fresh workspace.

Fix:
  execFileSync('git', ['push', '--set-upstream', 'origin', branch], { cwd: worktreePath });

init.ts creates a readline interface but only closes it on two explicit paths (empty repos early return, and after the service loop). If an exception propagates from anywhere inside the async prompt loops, rl.close() is never called and the process hangs waiting on stdin.

Fix: wrap the entire prompt sequence in try/finally:
  try {
    // ... all the await ask() loops ...
  } finally {
    rl.close();
  }

Remove the two explicit rl.close() calls and rely on the finally block.

sync.ts (agentSection) generates detach instructions for QA agents using a hardcoded prefix:

  git checkout --detach origin/${agent.reviews ? `agent/${agent.reviews}` : '<author-branch>'}

If the agent being reviewed has a custom branch field (not 'agent/<name>'), the generated CLAUDE.md will point to the wrong branch.

Fix: look up the actual branch from config:
  const reviewedAgent = config.agents.find(a => a.name === agent.reviews);
  const reviewedBranch = reviewedAgent?.branch ?? `agent/${agent.reviews}`;

start.ts:18 computes the coordinator's working directory as:

  const coordCwd = resolve(root, config.repos[Object.keys(config.repos)[0]]?.path ?? '.');

This ignores the coordinator agent's configured worktree field. It also duplicates the same Object.keys()[0] pattern from applyDefaults rather than reading the resolved value.

Fix: use the coordinator's worktree (already resolved by applyDefaults):
  const coordCwd = coordinator.worktree ?? resolve(root, '.');

watcher.ts:55 catches all errors from getNewlyClosedIssues and returns []:

  } catch {
    return [];
  }

If bd is not in PATH, or bd list fails for any reason, every file-change fires with no output and no coordinator notification. There is no log line to indicate the failure is happening.

Fix: log the error to stderr inside the catch block so the watcher window shows a diagnostic:
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('[camper-watch] bd list failed:', err);
    return [];
  }

sync.ts:71 parses git worktree list --porcelain by splitting on the first space:

  const idx = l.indexOf(' ');
  return [l.slice(0, idx), l.slice(idx + 1)];

When a line has no space — such as the 'bare' flag — indexOf returns -1. l.slice(0, -1) produces all-but-last-char as the key, and l.slice(0) returns the whole line as the value. The 'bare' line becomes key 'bar' → value 'bare', corrupting the parsed entry object.

Fix: guard the split:
  const idx = l.indexOf(' ');
  if (idx === -1) return [l, ''];
  return [l.slice(0, idx), l.slice(idx + 1)];

watcher.ts:25 seeds lastCheck and computes now as floored Unix seconds:

  let lastCheck = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);
  // later...
  const now = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);

In getNewlyClosedIssues, each issue's closed_at is also floored before comparing:
  const ts = Math.floor(new Date(issue.closed_at).getTime() / 1000);
  return ts > since;

If an issue closes at T+0.9s and lastCheck is T, both floor to T and T > T is false — the notification is silently dropped.

Fix: use >= instead of >, or keep millisecond precision throughout (remove the Math.floor calls and compare with Date.now()).

status() calls windowExists() for each agent and service, and windowExists() calls listWindows() internally — spawning a tmux process per check. The windows array is already fetched at the top of status() but never used for the per-item checks.

Fix: use the already-fetched windows array directly:
  const has = (name: string) => windows.includes(name);
  // replace all windowExists(session, x) calls with has(x)

This reduces N+1 tmux spawns to 1.

init.ts:99 falls back silently when the user types an unrecognized repo name:

  const repo = repos[repoInput] ? repoInput : repoNames[0];

If the user mistyped a repo name, the agent is silently assigned to the first repo with no warning. This produces a camper.json that doesn't match what the user intended.

Fix: show a warning or re-prompt:
  if (!repos[repoInput]) {
    console.warn(`  ⚠ Unknown repo '${repoInput}', defaulting to '${repoNames[0]}'`);
  }

bin/camper.ts hardcodes the version:

  program.version('0.1.0');

This will get out of sync with package.json as versions bump. Fix by reading it from the package file:

  import { createRequire } from 'module';
  const require = createRequire(import.meta.url);
  const { version } = require('../../package.json') as { version: string };
  program.version(version);

init.ts uses a dynamic import inside the async init function:

  const { createInterface } = await import('readline');

readline is a built-in Node.js module always available at startup. There is no benefit to a dynamic import here — it adds latency on first invocation and obscures the dependency.

Move to a static import at the top of the file:
  import { createInterface } from 'readline';

tmux.ts imports execSync from 'child_process' but never uses it:

  import { execSync, execFileSync } from 'child_process';

execSync is only used in init.ts. Remove from tmux.ts import.
